text=:Category: LinguisticDiscriminationInTheWild%0a:Title: American Promise: Idiris Code Switches%0a:Author: AlexisA%0a:Section: A%0a:Completed: 21.02.2021 - 20:27%0a:Status: complete%0a%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradeitem:)%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradingcomment:)%0a%0a----%0a%0a%0a%25blue%25 '''Grading History'''%0a%0a[[#history]]%0a#foxbegin 210504-191402-748940#%0a* [-04.05.2021 - 12:14-] || TA_audrey marked as complete%0a#foxend 210504-191402-748940#%0a[[#historyend]]%0a%0a%25blue%25 '''Comments for student'''%0a%0a[[#comments]]%0a%0a[[#commentsend]]%0a%0a----%0a----%0a!!%0a%0aSummary: \\%0a%0a[[#summary]]%0a%0aI share a video of a black student who attends Dalton explaining how he is made fun of by his peers in his neighborhood for talking "like a white boy."%0a%0a[[#summaryends]]%0a%0a----%0a[[#content]]%0a%0ahttps://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Zz-PyvtgCmQ%0a%0aThe above is a short clip from "American Promise," a documentary that follows two black boys through their experience at Dalton (one of the most prestigious private schools in the United States). In the video, one of the boys, Idris, explains that he is made fun of by some of the kids on his neighborhood basketball team because he "talk[s] like a white boy." %0a%0aIdris explains that he sometimes changes his dialect when in his primarily black neighborhood in order to blend in, using the example heɪjɒ̞ɔl: wʌs:ʌp for "hey y'all, what's up?" to simulate a version of African American Vernacular English. In particular, this example represents a lowering of the [ɔ] sound in y'all and consonant deletion between the final two words. Throughout the rest of the clip, he uses Standard American English.%0a%0aI chose this example, in part, because I thought it was interesting how it did not conform to our typical ideas about power dynamics in the context of linguistic discrimination. Rather than a person of privilege/power attempting to enforce the standards of their dialect on another person, it shows an example of people discriminating against another dialect because it represents a departure from what they consider normal for their community. I also wonder if it may reflect power dynamics in a different way, such as the members of his neighborhood feeling threatened that their teammate has access to different experiences and privileges than they do.%0a%0a[[#contentends]]%0a----%0a(:GradedBy: TA_audrey:)
